{"id":"1811.03432","submitter":"Pat Morin","authors":"Vida Dujmovi\\'c, Fabrizio Frati, Daniel Gon\\c{c}alves, Pat Morin, and\n  G\\\"unter Rote","title":"Every Collinear Set in a Planar Graph Is Free","comments":"29 pages, 12 figures","journal-ref":"Discrete and Computational Geometry 65 (2021), 999-1027","doi":"10.1007/s00454-019-00167-x","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We show that if a planar graph $G$ has a plane straight-line drawing in which\na subset $S$ of its vertices are collinear, then for any set of points, $X$, in\nthe plane with $|X|=|S|$, there is a plane straight-line drawing of $G$ in\nwhich the vertices in $S$ are mapped to the points in $X$. This solves an open\nproblem posed by Ravsky and Verbitsky in 2008. In their terminology, we show\nthat every collinear set is free.\n  This result has applications in graph drawing, including untangling, column\nplanarity, universal point subsets, and partial simultaneous drawings.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 8 Nov 2018 14:19:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-11"}
